So I realize that one of the larger benefits of using pathplanner this year is the ability to build a fully comprehensive autonomous routine using fullautobuilder instead of all the sequential command group bs of last year. There are a few things im confused about tho, starting off with marking events within the pathplanner application itself. What exactly does the wait behavior do? Whats the difference between parallel and sequential?

Other than that Im not really sure how you would pass in commands at these event markers. This is what I did purely based off of what I think it works like:

eventMap.put(“ScoreCube”, new RunCommand(scoringState::maxPos, arm, claw));
eventMap.put(“Balance”, balanceOnBeam);

and that eventmap is then used inside the SwerveAutoBuilder object i defined a few lines up. I named the strings exactly the same as the events themselves, does this mean that when the robot is at the “Balance” event the command ‘balanceOnBeam’ will run? Any help is appreciated.

The wait behavior can be used to add a wait time before or after the event. It can also be used to set the event to run for a certain amount of time. (The wiki provides more details on this. Link: Editor Modes · mjansen4857/pathplanner Wiki · GitHub)

Running the events in sequential or parallel is the same as sequential and parallel command groups, sequential runs them one after the other, parallel runs them all at once.

The code snippet you provided looks correct. When the robot gets to a point in the path where there is an event, it will run the command that is associated with it in the event map.
